    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "# Problem\r\n\r\nWhen trying out a scheme with non-alphabetic characters, it appears that the uri of the buffer gets translated into a relative path that gets resolved into an absolute path. Calls to functions like `vim.uri_from_bufnr` will prepend an absolute path to the name, breaking a variety of logic (e.g. `myscheme://hellotxt` becomes `file://path/to/myscheme1234://hello.txt`).\r\n\r\nAccording to [RFC 2396](http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc2396.txt), Appendix A:\r\n\r\n> scheme        = alpha *( alpha | digit | \"+\" | \"-\" | \".\" )\r\n\r\nThe scheme should start with a letter (upper or lower case), and can contains letters (still upper and lower case), number, \"+\", \"-\" and \".\".\r\n\r\nIt appears that providing characters other than alphabetic (numbers, +, etc) will cause issues. Happens with `nvim -u NONE`.\r\n\r\n# Steps to reproduce\r\n\r\n### Step 1: Test `vim.uri_from_bufnr` using regular name\r\n\r\nOpen a fresh buffer and set its name to the relative path of \"hello.txt\":\r\n\r\n```lua\r\nvim.api.nvim_buf_set_name(0, 'hello.txt')\r\n```\r\n\r\nPrint out the uri to observe the default is to include both the `file` scheme and provide an absolute path relative to the `cwd` of neovim:\r\n\r\n```lua\r\n-- Prints file:///path/to/hello.txt\r\n-- where /path/to is the cwd\r\nprint(vim.uri_from_bufnr(0))\r\n```\r\n\r\n### Step 2: Test `vim.uri_from_bufnr` using alphabetic scheme\r\n\r\nSet the buffer name to some scheme with just alphabetic characters like `distant`:\r\n\r\n```lua\r\nvim.api.nvim_buf_set_name(0, 'distant://hello.txt')\r\n```\r\n\r\nPrint out the uri to observe that a scheme is detected and properly used:\r\n\r\n```lua\r\n-- Prints distant://hello.txt\r\nprint(vim.uri_from_bufnr(0))\r\n```\r\n\r\n### Step 3: Test `vim.uri_from_bufnr` using alphabetic scheme that includes +, number, or some combination\r\n\r\nSet the buffer name to some scheme with a `+` character in the middle like `distant+1234`:\r\n\r\n```lua\r\nvim.api.nvim_buf_set_name(0, 'distant+1234://hello.txt')\r\n```\r\n\r\nPrint out the uri to observe that a scheme is not properly detected and an absolute path is still provided:\r\n\r\n```lua\r\n-- Prints file:///path/to/distant+1234://hello.txt\r\n-- where /path/to is the cwd\r\nprint(vim.uri_from_bufnr(0))\r\n```\r\n\r\nNote that you can remove the + and just include numbers AFTER the first letter have have the same issue.\r\n\r\n# Expected behavior\r\n\r\nSetting the buffer name to something like `distant+1234://hello.txt` should not result in functions like `vim.uri_from_bufnr` treating them like a relative file path with a scheme of `file`.\r\n\r\n### Step 3: Test `vim.uri_from_bufnr` using alphabetic scheme that includes +, number, or some combination\r\n\r\nSet the buffer name to some scheme with a `+` character in the middle like `distant+1234`:\r\n\r\n```lua\r\nvim.api.nvim_buf_set_name(0, 'distant+1234://hello.txt')\r\n```\r\n\r\nPrint out the uri to observe that it is respected:\r\n\r\n```lua\r\n-- Prints distant+1234://hello.txt\r\nprint(vim.uri_from_bufnr(0))\r\n```\r\n\r\n# System Details\r\n\r\n### Neovim version (nvim -v)\r\n\r\n0.9.0\r\n\r\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\r\n\r\nNo, vim works using `:file` and `:echo bufname()`.\r\n\r\nVIM - Vi IMproved 9.0 (2022 Jun 28, compiled Aug 17 2022 21:21:22)\r\n\r\n```vim\r\n\" Prints out distant://hello.txt\r\n:file distant://hello.txt\r\n:echo bufname()\r\n\r\n\" Prints out distant+1234://hello.txt\r\n:file distant+1234://hello.txt\r\n:echo bufname()\r\n```\r\n\r\n### Operating system/version\r\n\r\nmacOS 12.6\r\n\r\n### Terminal name/version\r\n\r\nwezterm 20221119-145034-49b9839f\r\n\r\n### $TERM environment variable\r\n\r\nxterm-256color\r\n\r\n### Installation\r\n\r\nhomebrew",
